# Parameter passing technique in Java:
   Default Technique – Java uses "Pass by Value" (Call by Value) for all parameters.
   No Pass by Address – Java doesn’t support pointers, so "Pass by Address" is invalid.
   Always Pass by Value – Whether passing a variable or reference, a copy of the value is sent.

1) Passing Object as "Pass by Value" in Java
   In Java, when you pass an object to a method, you are actually passing a copy of the reference (memory address) to that object.
    The original reference and the copied reference both point to the same object in memory.
   Changes made inside the method affect the original object because both references point to the same memory location.
   Reassigning the reference inside the method does not affect the original reference outside.


2) Passing Array to Method in Java
    Arrays in Java are objects, so when you pass an array to a method, you pass a copy of the reference (similar to objects).
    Modifying array elements inside the method affects the original array.
    Reassigning the array reference inside the method does not affect the original reference.